<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Tribute Page</title>
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Open+Sans:400,700" rel="stylesheet">
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: 'Open Sans', sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      background-color: #f9f9f9;
      color: #333;
    }

    #main {
      max-width: 800px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 20px;
      text-align: center;
    }

    #title {
      font-size: 2em;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
    }

    #img-div {
      margin: 20px 0;
    }

    #image {
      display: block;
      max-width: 100%;
      height: auto;
      margin: 0 auto;
      border-radius: 8px;
    }

    #img-caption {
      margin-top: 10px;
      font-style: italic;
      color: #555;
    }

    #tribute-info {
      margin: 30px 0;
      text-align: left;
      line-height: 1.6;
    }

    #tribute-link {
      display: inline-block;
      margin-top: 20px;
      text-decoration: none;
      color: #0066cc;
      font-weight: bold;
    }

    #tribute-link:hover {
      text-decoration: underline;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <main id="main">
    <h1 id="title">Ada Lovelace</h1>
    <figure id="img-div">
      <img id="image" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a4/Ada_Lovelace_portrait.jpg" alt="Portrait of Ada Lovelace">
      <figcaption id="img-caption">Ada Lovelace, often regarded as the first computer programmer.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <div id="tribute-info">
      Ada Lovelace (1815–1852) was an English mathematician and writer, chiefly known for her work on Charles Babbage's proposed mechanical general-purpose computer, the Analytical Engine. She was the first to recognize that the machine had applications beyond pure calculation, and published the first algorithm intended to be carried out by such a machine. Her visionary ideas laid the foundation for modern computing.
    </div>
    <a id="tribute-link" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ada_Lovelace" target="_blank">Learn more about Ada Lovelace</a>
  </main>
</body>
</html>

